            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the people of Judah",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] ‘The children of the captivity’ are here given the name of the old southern kingdom. Cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ezra 4:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "troubled",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] so R.V.: marg. Or ‘",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "terrified",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "’. There are two readings. The reading of the Hebrew text or K’thib gives a word that does not occur elsewhere in the O.T. but is connected with a substantive rendered ‘terror’ (R.V. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 17:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The reading of the Hebrew tradition or K’ri, preserved with the text, gives an otherwise unused form of a common word meaning ‘to trouble’. In all probability the letters of the unused root were transposed by a scribe so as to give the familiar root; preference should be given to the harder rendering, ‘terrified them from building’.",
        "children": []
